h3. Issue Summary

The "[Edit Issue|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/8.1.2/#api/2/issue-editIssue]" REST API documentation has some invalid JSON in the example request body
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Search the example for the enpoint /rest/api/2/issue/\{issueIdOrKey}/editmeta

h3. Expected Results

The "properties" section should look as below:
{noformat}
   "properties":[  
      {  
         "key":"key1",
         "value":"properties can be set at issue create or update time"
      },
      {  
         "key":"key2",
         "value":"and there can be multiple properties"
      }
   ]
}
{noformat}
 
h3. Actual Results

The "property" section shows:
{noformat}
"properties":[
  {"key":"key1","value":'properties' : 'can be set at issue create or update time'},
  {"key":"key2","value":'and' : 'there can be multiple properties'}
]
{noformat}


h3. Workaround
Use the  correct syntax

 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Go to Issues > Search for Issues page.
 # Log any work against any issue.
 # In the Advanced search, enter the following JQL (as an example) to retrieve the issue where a work log has just been added
{code:java}
project = SSP and worklogDate >= 2019-07-01 {code}

 # Go to the Projects admin page and archive the project.
 # On the Archived projects page, select the same project and restore it. Re-index the project.
 # Go back to Issues > Search for Issues page and use the same JQL from step 3:
{code:java}
project = SSP and worklogDate >= 2019-07-01  {code}

h3. Expected Results
 * The issue(s) that contained work log data will be returned

h3. Actual Results
 * No issues are returned

h3. Workaround

For now, the workaround is to simply archive and then restore an issue. This operation will reindex the worklog for the particular issue.

Doing it for each issue could be inconvenient but you can use the following REST APIs to achieve this: 


1. Archive Issue:
{code:java}
https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/8.1.0/?_ga=2.21004027.1799173514.1563759460-810944152.1559651610#api/2/issue-archiveIssue{code}
2. Restore Issue:
{code:java}
https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/8.1.0/?_ga=2.21004027.1799173514.1563759460-810944152.1559651610#api/2/issue-restoreIssue{code}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server including Data Center*.
This request to also covers ONLY Aurora Serverless deployments, for Aurora alone see [JRASERVER-41985|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-41985]
{panel}

Amazon is using a compatible database server called Aurora Serverless, for use in the AWS. It would be great if we can have support for this database, which according to Amazon, is designed to be compatible with MySQL and Postgres

h3. Issue Summary
When installing Jira from a zip file or tarball, using {{service.bat}} to create the service will succeed, but the service won't start.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Set the {{JRE_HOME}} environment variable
# Run {{$jira-install/bin/service.bat install Jira}}

h3. Expected Results
The service starts successfully.

h3. Actual Results
The service does not start successfully.

The error message can be observed when attempting to start the service:
{code}
The "Atlassian JIRA service terminated with the following service-specific error:
Incorrect function."
{code}

h3. Workaround

# Edit {{service.bat}}, and find the following line:
{code}
set "EXECUTABLE=%CATALINA_HOME%\bin\tomcat8.exe "
{code}
# Change this line to:
{code}
set "EXECUTABLE=%CATALINA_HOME%\bin\tomcat8.exe.x64"
{code}
# Remove the original service, using {{service.bat uninstall jira}}
# Create the service again, using {{service.bat install Jira}}
